                     −2 short-circuit current density (


                              J

                                 sc



                     ), 0.73 V open-circuit voltage (


                              V

                                 oc



                     ), and 56% fill factor (

                           FF

                     ). Mandal et al. [13] theoretically studied GQD-porphyrin nanocomposite DSSCs. Different GQD-porphyrin nanocomposites were designed either by changing the GQD size or by attaching the porphyrin moiety with different functional groups. They prove that the nanocomposites can form type-I/type-II nanohybrids and that the GQD-porphyrin nanohybrid material with a larger GQD is a good contender for efficient DSSCs. Gao et al. [11] theoretically improved the efficiency of DSSCs by applying cir-coronene graphene oxide quantum dots (GOQDs) and tetraphenylporphyrin (TPP) as nanocomposite sensitizers. The first reported cause of improvements is the enhanced absorbance in the visible (Vis) region. Their results indicated that the GOQD(18OH)-TPP nanocomposite has the most efficient electrochemical parameters, such as a larger driving force (DF) and larger light harvesting ability. In another effort by the group of Gao et al. [10], another nanocomposite material was theoretically designed, i.e., GQDs with carbazole–carbazole dyes. The designed nanocomposites were found to possess the appropriate energy levels, and their absorbance of light fell in the Vis and near IR (NIR) regions. Li et al. [23] performed an interesting investigation regarding the possible linkage configuration between the GQDs and dye. They tested three linkage types and calculated the photoelectric conversion efficiency and optical and electrical properties. The amidation linkage (amide linkage) was proven to be the most efficient linkage due to the improvement in the absorption intensity and the maximum photon-generated current and can decrease the electron recombination rate. In the work of Zhao et al. [24], GQDs were corroborated with different D-π-A type triazatruxene (TAT)-based organic dyes. It was found that the GQD/dye possesses a high absorption peak in the UV region, improved molecular molar extinction coefficients, larger light harvesting efficiency (LHE), and improved charge transfer performance and regeneration ability compared to the isolated dyes. They also successfully predicted the power conversion efficiency (

                           η

                     ) and other related parameters. One of their designed nanocomposites reached 

                           η

                      values reaching 17.4%. Kumara et al. [25] extracted NDs from Ixora (IX) flowers and characterized them by UV–Vis, TLC, FTIR, and fluorescence characterization tools, and complete data on the use of these NDs in a photovoltaic device were presented. The four NDs were identified as aurone (ND1), pelargonidin (ND2), cyanidin (ND3) and malvidin (ND4) (see Fig. 1
                     ). The reported power conversion efficiency values of the resultant photosensitized cells are less than 1% and range from 0.203 to 0.951%. The reported [25] electronic, optical, and photovoltaic parameters of the DSSCs sensitized with NDi (i = 1–4) are recorded in Table 1
                     .

The free components of the final NDIX-GQD-TiO2 complex, including the four natural IX flower dyes (ND1 to ND4), GQD, and TiO2 cluster, were optimized free of geometrical constraints using DFT using Becke’s three parameter exchange functional, the Lee-Yang-Parr correlation functional (B3LYP) [28,29]. B3LYP is a consistent functional that has usually been used in the study of similar nanostructures [30–33]. The applied basis sets were 6-31G(d,p), Pople’s split-valence double-zeta (

                           ζ

                     ) basis set with d and p polarization orbitals for C, H, N, and O atoms, and Los Alamos National Laboratory with double zeta (DZ) (LANL2DZ) and pseudopotential basis sets for titanium and iodine atoms [34]. In these calculations, TiO2 is represented by a (Ti2O4H)3 cluster. The solvation effects were simulated using the conductor-like solvation model (C-PCM) developed in the framework of the polarizable continuum model (PCM) [35,36] in methanol (CH3OH; 

                           ε
