                           33.0
                           )

                     .

The main key factor of a photosensitizer to be an efficient one is to be able to harvest as much as possible of the solar spectrum, i.e., to efficiently absorb light in the visible (Vis) and near infrared (NIR) regions upon photoexcitation. The simulated absorption spectra of isolated GQD, NDIX, and nanocomposites of GQD-NDIX obtained at CAM-B3LYP and C-PCM/CAM-B3LYP with 6-31G(d,p) (a) in the gas phase and (b) in methanol solvent are depicted in Fig. 7 , and the detailed absorption properties, such as the maximum absorption wavelengths (
λ
max
), oscillator strengths (
f
) of GQD, NDIX, and nanocomposites of GQD-NDIX in methanol at C-PCM/TDCAM-B3LYP with 6-31G(d,p) and LANL2DZ basis sets, are listed in Table 3 . The reliability of the calculated absorption wavelengths and, thus, the used level of theory is evident from the deviations from the experimental ones. The maximum deviation equals 36% while the minimum and thus the better agreement equals 10%, see Table 3.

Moreover, the lifetime of the excited electron (
τ
), see Equation 4 (DFT details SD), is an important property that determines the efficiency of photoexcited electrons from the sensitizer’s LUMO to TiO2′s CB. Since the shortest time the photoexcited electron spends in the LUMOs, the more efficient it will be injected into the CB; conversely, if the excited electron’s lifetime is long, the more chance it will deexcite and combine with the hole in the sensitizer’s HOMO state [27,51–53]. From Table SD3 and Fig. 9 , the photoexcited electron lifetimes of the nanocomposites are in the range of 0.56 to 1.16 ns (ns), while for the NDs of the isolates, the range of these values is from 2.46 to 4.22 ns. Therefore, the shorter emission wavelengths and larger oscillation strengths of the nanocomposites compensate for the fact that the lifetimes of the photoexcited electrons of the nanocomposites are significantly shorter than those of isolated NDs. This will assure an effective electron injection process in the former systems and therefore solar cells with highly efficient performance.

It is essential to induce an effective force to separate the charges (holes from electrons) so that the electrons can be successfully injected, which can be predicted to occur if there is significant intramolecular charge transfer (IACT). IACT is investigated through electron density difference plots between the ground and first excited states (
Δ ρ
) of the isolated NDIX and nanocomposites of GQD-NDIX in methanol at the C-PCM/TDCAM-B3LYP with a 6-31G(d,p) basis set (Figure SD3). The blue and cyan colors indicate regions of increasing and decreasing electron densities, respectively. A decrease in electron density occurs in the electron-rich regions, whereas an increase in electron density occurs in the electron-poor regions [23]. To a large extent, the separation of charges in the isolated NDIX is not present since the whole skeletons of molecules are electron-rich and electron-poor regions simultaneously. In the nanocomposites, separation of charges is not observed since the electron-rich/poor regions are mainly delocalized on the GQD skeletons. However, the accumulation of charges (holes/electrons) on the GQDs and the nondelocalization of these charges on the ND can present a separation of charges on the nanocomposite framework. Therefore, the nanocomposites show the desired charge separation, which is necessary for electron/hole transfer.
